  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the procedure to apply to an RTI?",
  "response": "The Right to Information (RTI) Act in India allows citizens to request information from public authorities. Here's a step-by-step procedure to apply for RTI:\n\n1. **Identify the Information Needed**: Clearly define the information you want from a public authority. Ensure that the information falls under the purview of the RTI Act.\n\n2. **Find the Appropriate Public Authority**: Determine which public authority holds the information you need. You can find this information on the official website of the government or public authority.\n\n3. **Draft the RTI Application**:\n   - **Format**: You can write your application in plain paper or use an RTI application format if available.\n   - **Content**: Include the following details:\n     - Your name and address (address should be complete to receive a response).\n     - The date of the application.\n     - A clear description of the information sought.\n     - Any specific details that can help in locating the required information.\n     - Mention whether you require the information in a particular format, if applicable.\n\n4. **Submit the Application**: \n   - You can submit your RTI application in person at the office of the public authority or send it by post.\n   - In many states, you may also have the option to apply online through the official RTI portals.\n\n5. **Pay the Fee**: There is typically a nominal fee associated with submitting an RTI application (generally \u20b910). This can usually be paid via cash, a postal order, or a bank draft. Some states have specific rules for fees, so check those.\n\n6. **Receive an Acknowledgment**: If submitting in person, ensure you get a stamped acknowledgment of your application. If you apply by post, retain the receipt for tracking.\n\n7. **Wait for a Response**: The public authority is required to respond within 30 days (or 48 hours for information concerning the life and liberty of a person). \n\n8. **Receive Information**: The information can be provided in the specified format and may include copies of documents, data, etc. If the information is denied, you should receive a reason for the denial.\n\n9. **Appeal if Necessary**: If you are not satisfied with the response or if no response is received, you can file an appeal with the First Appellate Authority within the public authority. If dissatisfied with that appeal\u2019s outcome, you can further appeal to the Central or State Information Commission.\n\nMake sure to check the specific guidelines and provisions of the RTI Act as they can vary slightly depending on the state or the type of authority you are dealing with.",
